{"cursor":"4583","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn linear algebra, two n-by-n matrices A and B are called 'similar' if\n: \\! B = P^{-1} A P\nfor some invertible n-by-n matrix P. Similar matrices represent the same\nlinear transformation under two different bases, with P being the change of\nbasis matrix.\n\nThe matrix P is sometimes called a 'similarity transformation'. In the context\nof matrix groups, similarity is sometimes referred to as '[[conjugacy\nclass|conjugacy]]', with similar matrices being 'conjugate'.\n","linknr":144,"url":"Matrix_similarity","recorded":1362671831,"links":28,"instances":["linear_algebra","linear_algebra","linear_algebra","mathematics","linear_algebra"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Matrices"],"headings":["Properties","Notes","Other areas","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/b/1/9b139fa04a262afc853790043353db63.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["matrix","mathematics"],["basis","linear_algebra"],["rank","linear_algebra"],["trace","linear_algebra"],["minimal_polynomial","linear_algebra"]],"members":["trace","basis","rank","matrix","minimal_polynomial"],"related":["Linear_algebra","Matrix_(mathematics)","Invertible_matrix","Linear_map","Basis_(linear_algebra)","Change_of_basis","Matrix_group","Equivalence_relation","Rank_(linear_algebra)","Determinant","Trace_(linear_algebra)","Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors","Characteristic_polynomial","Minimal_polynomial_(linear_algebra)","Similarity_invariant","Smith_normal_form","Elementary_divisors","Linear_map","Basis_of_a_vector_space","Automorphism","Associative_algebra","Diagonalizable_matrix","Diagonal_matrix","Complex_number","Algebraically_closed_field","Jordan_form","Rational_canonical_form","Smith_normal_form","Subfield","If_and_only_if","Transpose",